column1: Before 1 April 2019, how many countries will formally progress in the NATO accession process?
column6: ['Non-US Politics']
column11: Formal progression in the NATO accession process consists of a country: reaching a new stage of any of the seven stages listed under the accession process section (NATO); receiving an invitation to participate in a Membership Action Plan (NATO); or entering into Intensified Dialogue (Project Gutenberg). Countries will only be counted once. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: Currently, four partner countries have declared their aspirations to NATO membership: Bosnia and Herzegovina, Georgia, the Republic of North Macedonia and Ukraine. Under Zelensky, Razumkov said, Ukraine would continue aspiring to join the European Union and NATO, but it would hold a referendum on the issues only when the chance of doing so was realistic. There are currently 4 countries looking to join NATO; Bosnia and Herzegovina, Georgia, the Republic of North Macedonia, and Ukraine. While Ukraine is in the midst of an election, both the incumbent Poroshenko and his leading opponent Zalensky have expressed a desire to join NATO, although no specific timeline has been given, and Zalensky, who recently won a run-off election, has stated that he would wait until the time is right. So while an actual timeline is up in the air, it seems likely that whomever wins the presidential election will seek to hold ascension talks with NATO as well as MAP, due to Poroshenko meeting with NATO this past December, in which NATO reaffirmed support for Ukraine against Russian aggression. NATO announced at a meeting in December 2018 that it is prepared to accept the submission of an ANP by Bosnia and Herzegovina. While some members of the presidency welcomed this new development and expressed hope that state institutions would begin developing an ANP, the leader of the Serb nationaalists in the presidency has repeatedly been against NATO membership. It’s clear that any closer movement by Bosnia and Herzegovina will be contingent on dealing with conflict amongst its different ethnic groups. Due to the ongoing situation in Ukraine, I find it doubtful that Georgia will make any serious moves to join NATO before April 1st. Allowing Georgia to go further along in the membership process would place pressure on Russia that could impede negotiations over the Ukrainian conflict and impede NATO operations in other areas, so both Georgia and NATO are better served maintaining their current cooperative relationship. The Republic of North Macedonia formally signed a letter for ascension in February, and will likely be a full member by the end of the year. https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/zelensky-face-poroshenko-ukraine-run-exit-poll-190331171422240.html https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/topics_49212.htm https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-polytics/2671315-poroshenko-we-will-either-reaffirm-course-for-eu-nato-or-return-to-2013.html https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/topics_49127.htm https://www.rferl.org/a/nato-gives-bosnia-green-light-to-move-toward-membership/29639709.html https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/06/world/europe/north-macedonia-nato-russia.html

Currently, there are 4 NATO aspirant countries. In the past, seventeen countries have joined NATO. With my own research, many, but not all, countries move forward in the process within the year they applied (the Visegrád Group ascending after 10 months, the Vilnius Group ascending after about 8 months, Montenegro after 13 months).

Reviewing the two prior rounds of NATO enlargement, 2004 and 2009, we can identify two important trends in the process for NATO integration. First, the process almost always takes more than 5 years, due to the need for ratification by every existing member and the need for the country wishing to access to NATO to conform its armed forces to a certain degree of interoperability before being allowed to move forward. Secondly, As we can see from the most recent two NATO members, Albania and Croatia, even when all requirements are met formal accession does not usually occur by independent nations, as NATO seems to have a tendency to "group" countries together and have multiple formally become members at the same time. Given this, I would rate the likelihood of the only reasonable candidate for NATO accession, N. Macedonia, as unlikely before the date required, as such an event would constitute a shift in procedure for NATO which generally is a very procedural institution.

Of the four countries currently listed by NATO as aspirational (Bosnia and Herzegovina, Georgia, the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, and Ukraine), Macedonia is the furthest along, based on statements by NATO (https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/topics_49212.htm). However, the recent failure of the referendum on Macedonia's name change (https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/failed-macedonian-referendum-181001185416308.html) further confirms the already apparent difficulties in getting though even this first condition required to begin the formal accession process as laid out in July when the NATO Secretary General announced NATO's invitation to the government in Skopje to begin talks (https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_157315.htm). The referendum also showed significant popular support for NATO accession—and since the referendum was only advisory, not binding, there is still ample room for progress in the name-change debate. But, resolving this key dispute and formally amending Macedonia’s constitution to reflect the new name before April seems like a tall order.

Currently, four partner countries have declared their aspirations to NATO membership: Bosnia and Herzegovina, Georgia, the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia and Ukraine, but the country that has the highest likelihood of gaining membership by April 2019 is Macedonia. Macedonia's greatest challenge that could possibly hinder this accession is the conflict over the name of the country. NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg called on Macedonians at the end of September to vote in a referendum to embrace a deal on its name with neighboring Greece and join the defense alliance. However, Macedonians have rejected an attempt to change the name of their nation to North Macedonia, which could mean their country will remain outside the regional power blocs of NATO and the European Union.

Given recent developments in Eastern Europe such as Georgia's revolution and Macedonia's referendum, there are only two possible countries that might join NATO before April 2019. However, the internal politics of the aforementioned states are not likely to let the governments make a commitment to NATO their priorities in the nearest future. When it comes to Georgia, the new government is currently preoccupied with eradicating corruption and their domestic situation as a whole. Making international commitments as big as joining NATO are not likely to be in the cards for Georgia for at least another year. However, once the internal overhaul is over, Georgia is likely to be the next country of the Eastern block to join NATO. Given Macedonia's recent referendum vote on the name change of the state and a very low turn out, it is obvious that Macedonia is likely to be preoccupied with internal challenges for the nearest future. In particular, the challenge is to accommodate for the needs and repair relations between the majority population and Serb minorities. Thus, the internal struggles will slow down Macedonia's commitment to NATO.

They currently have a slim majority expected to agree to the name change deal agreed upon withe the gov of Greece, but they need 50% of people to actually go out and vote to make. Probability is probably 85% there, I would guess, especially since ethnic Albanians make up 25% of the Macedonian population and largely support the measure. For the 30-40% of the rest of Macedonia to turn out for the vote, even if mostly from the younger or middle generations, seems, seems likely. However, the president has remained firm in opposition and is boycotting the vote out of country (maybe wise), and Russia is still pumping money into campaigning locally against it, as are many Western countries. If it passes but does't have the voter turnout necessary to ratify, then I think they'll reschedule again shortly after the New Year. But it sounds like enough people are grudgingly or significantly motivated by economic and security benefits that they'll go with it for now. Might be a sticky point later. Still, if it passes, it has to be ratified by the Macedonian parliament (likely if it passes) and then be voted on in Greece as well, and ultimate, I think, Greece would have to agree with the Nato accession step. At least they've been the roadblock for the last 3 decades. But I imagine NATO is leaning hard on them, and Greece doesn't really have a lot of public or political power to stand alone against their European allies in this and probably have agreed enough to (grudgingly) move forward if Macedonia ends up agreeing.

Progression in the NATO accession process is similar to the minor leagues in baseball. Having a chance to join NATO is a big deal. The accession process is slow and moving up in status towards membership requires the subject country to meet criteria proposed by every NATO country and general guidelines. Strategically and politically, Bosnia and Herzegovina is the logical choice. The remaining countries currently in the accession process are Macedonia, Georgia and the Ukraine. Each of the former nations do not meet portions of the general criteria or have disputes with current NATO members. Furthermore, moving Bosnia and Herzegovina up the ladder would create a stronger Western block on the map and move a Slavic country closer to committing to the West. Some constituencies of the country oppose NATO membership, but they are a minority and guaranteed Western aid in perpetuity is hard to turn down.

North Macedonia might achieve some progress; Bosnia too; Moldova is a good candidate for progress; Russian opposition is real but its influence, extremely limited; others (Sweden, Finland) - maybe, depending on Russian (perceived) behavior in Ukraine and Baltics; it is highly unlikely that NATO stops the enlargement process completely as it would mean the end of the alliance; at the same time, we're approaching the overreach so leaders (esp. in Europe) will be careful not to provoke Russia and minimize costs of further enlargement. So somewhere midway are the most likely answers.

The name of Macedonia has been a source of contention between the two countries for decades, frustrating hopes of the tiny but strategically placed Balkan state of joining NATO, and the European Union, where Greece has veto rights.

There is an increasing possibility that the FYROM/Greece name dispute could reach a resolution this summer. Expect NATO progress would follow reasonably swiftly if a deal is struck. Still a way to go but a lot of the chatter underlying the news is that progress is very real https://www.reuters.com/article/us-macedonia-greece-name/macedonian-pm-sees-solution-to-name-dispute-with-greece-in-june-idUSKCN1II1OF

Of the four countries NATO has recognized with membership ambitions, Ukraine is too much of a mess, Bosnia and Herzegovina has internal political disagreements, Macedonia has the name dispute, and Georgia seems very quiet (I can't find anything recent of the subject). While its possible Macedonia could resolve the name dispute and start the accession process or Sweden could start the process, stasis always seems more likely.

In an increasingly dangerous Europe, NATO is looking to expand the alliance, especially in the Balkans, right in the back yard in an increasingly aggressive Russia. Macedonia, a MAP (Member Accession Action Plan) member since 1999, would be an increasingly valuable 'base' for NATO in the Balkans. The recent recognition of Macedonia by Turkey in a decisive step toward accession, but Greece's refusal to recognize the country is a major drawback. Additionally, recent Democratic Backsliding in Bosnia has been a dissuading factor in its case for accession to NATO membership, but NATO's desperate need for a foothold in the Balkans could lead to its timely accession.
